s about sharing generate social transformations that result in inequality and increasingly encompassing socio-political structures. Rethinking Social Evolution is a wide-ranging exploration of how language and increased cognitive abilities constitute the motor of social evolution. Drawing on a wide range of ethnographic case studies, Rousseau offers a better understanding of how modern societies are the result of choices by people who both collaborate and compete.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAutochtonesxMoeurs et coutumes. 0aIndians of North AmericaxSocial life and customs. 0aIndiens d'AmériquexMoeurs et coutumesxAmérique du Nord. 0aIndigenous peoplesxSocial life and customs. 0aSocial evolutionvCase studies. 0aSocial evolutionxCase studies. 0aSocial systemsvCase studies. 0aSocial systemsxCase studies. 0aSystèmes sociauxxCroissance. 0aSystèmes sociaux. 0aÉvolution socialexCas, Études de. 0aÉvolution sociale. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356018540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773560185423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773560185/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles